---
import Section from "~/components/Section.astro";
import Stage from "~/components/Stage.astro";
import Callout from "~/components/Callout.astro";
---

<Section id="padding" num="08" title="Query padding — the privacy linchpin">
  <p>
    Suppose Alice has 3 real scripthashes to look up in this round. Each one
    lands in a (different) PBC group out of <code>K = 75</code>. A naive
    client would send 3 queries — one per real item, none for the other 72
    groups. A server watching the wire would learn that Alice's 3 items live
    in <em>those specific</em> 3 groups. Across enough rounds, this leaks
    information about which groups — and which address patterns — she cares
    about.
  </p>

  <p>
    BitcoinPIR forbids that. In every round, the client sends <em>exactly</em>
    <code>K = 75</code> INDEX queries, <em>exactly</em> <code>K_CHUNK = 80</code>
    CHUNK queries, and <em>exactly</em> one Merkle-sibling query per tree
    level being verified. Real queries go into their computed PBC groups;
    every empty group gets a <strong>dummy query with a random DPF key</strong>.
    From the server's point of view, the traffic is identical for any number
    of real queries from 0 up to the batch limit.
  </p>

  <pre><code>{`// pir-sdk-client/src/dpf.rs:199 — INDEX padding loop
for b in 0..k {
    for h in 0..INDEX_CUCKOO_NUM_HASHES {
        let alpha = if b == assigned_group {
            my_locs[h]                          // real query
        } else {
            rng.next_u64() % bins as u64        // dummy random alpha
        };
        let (k0, k1) = dpf.gen(alpha, dpf_n);
        s0_group.push(k0.to_bytes());
        s1_group.push(k1.to_bytes());
    }
}`}</code></pre>

  <Stage
    caption="Left: server sees 3 real queries and can pinpoint the active groups. Right: server sees 75 indistinguishable queries — real and dummy are the same wire bytes."
    label="Unpadded versus padded queries"
  >
    <svg viewBox="0 0 680 260" role="img"
      aria-label="Side-by-side: unpadded query reveals which groups hold real items; padded query makes every group indistinguishable."
      data-anim="padding">
      <!-- unpadded -->
      <g transform="translate(0,10)">
        <text x="150" y="16" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-label"
          fill="var(--danger)">UNPADDED — 3 real queries</text>
        {Array.from({ length: 75 }).map((_, i) => {
          const real = i === 12 || i === 34 || i === 57;
          const col = i % 15;
          const row = Math.floor(i / 15);
          return (
            <rect x={8 + col * 19} y={30 + row * 22} width="15" height="15"
              rx="2"
              fill={real ? "var(--danger)" : "transparent"}
              stroke={real ? "var(--danger)" : "var(--border)"}
              stroke-width="1"/>
          );
        })}
        <text x="150" y="190" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10"
          class="svg-label" fill="var(--danger)">
          server: "groups 12, 34, 57 are active"
        </text>
      </g>

      <line x1="340" y1="10" x2="340" y2="240" stroke="var(--border)"
        stroke-dasharray="3 4"/>

      <!-- padded -->
      <g transform="translate(360,10)">
        <text x="150" y="16" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-label"
          fill="var(--ok)">PADDED — 75 queries, all look alike</text>
        {Array.from({ length: 75 }).map((_, i) => {
          const real = i === 12 || i === 34 || i === 57;
          const col = i % 15;
          const row = Math.floor(i / 15);
          return (
            <g class={real ? "pcell pcell-real" : "pcell pcell-dummy"}>
              <rect x={8 + col * 19} y={30 + row * 22} width="15" height="15"
                rx="2" fill="var(--ok)" stroke="var(--ok)" stroke-width="1"
                opacity={real ? 1 : 0.55}/>
            </g>
          );
        })}
        <text x="150" y="190" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10"
          class="svg-label" fill="var(--ok)">
          server: "something happened in every group, somewhere"
        </text>
      </g>
    </svg>
  </Stage>

  <Callout label="Not optional" kind="danger">
    <p>
      Padding <em>looks</em> wasteful — you generate and transmit 72 extra
      DPF keys for no "useful" data — but those 72 dummies are what make the
      3 real queries private. If you drop them, the server can count real
      queries and correlate them across rounds. <strong>Padding is the
      privacy. It is not a performance bug to be optimized away.</strong>
      The same rule applies to CHUNK (<code>K_CHUNK = 80</code>) and Merkle
      rounds.
    </p>
  </Callout>
</Section>

<style>
  [data-anim="padding"] .pcell { opacity: 0; }
  [data-anim="padding"].play .pcell-real {
    animation: dummyin 0.01s linear 0.2s forwards;
  }
  @keyframes dummyin {
    0%   { opacity: 0; }
    100% { opacity: 1; }
  }
  @media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
    [data-anim="padding"] .pcell { opacity: 1 !important; }
  }
</style>

<script is:inline>
  document.querySelectorAll('[data-anim="padding"]').forEach((svg) => {
    const stage = svg.closest("[data-stage]");
    const cells = svg.querySelectorAll(".pcell-dummy");
    const reducedMotion = window.matchMedia("(prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)")
      .matches;
    const run = () => {
      svg.classList.remove("play");
      void svg.getBoundingClientRect();
      svg.classList.add("play");
      if (reducedMotion) return;
      // stagger dummy cells with JS for a clean wash
      cells.forEach((c, i) => {
        c.style.animation = "none";
        void c.getBoundingClientRect();
        c.style.animation = `dummyin 0.25s var(--ease) ${0.25 + i * 0.015}s forwards`;
      });
    };
    stage?.addEventListener("stage:visible", run);
    svg.addEventListener("click", run);
  });
</script>
